Good, but not great. Travel is quite cumbersome. You get a map to refer to, 
but you can't fast-travel - you have to take the long way EVERY time. 
Without the map, I'd have gotten so frustrated, I would have uninstalled, 
and I love how complex the Room games are (which you need to play - they 
are beyond awesome!). But you spend most of your game time running around. 
That gets old fast. The puzzles are mostly well-designed, but a couple are 
rather arcane, and one, I would never have figured out without a hint, and 
I'm not talking about the buried item (either finding it or opening it). 
It's not overly difficult, but there will be times you get frustrated 
because a good solution just won't work. You have to solve it the way the 
game wants. And you can't solve a puzzle without getting the accompanying 
journal entry. Gorgeous graphics and good music. Not a bad way to spend an 
hour or two.

I can't say enough about how much I like this game. It's beautifully crafted and executed, everything from its graphics to its music, all are stellar and make for a total immersion experience.  The game itself is intriguing and fascinating. It's challenging, but not in an "I'm getting frustrated" sort of way. Rather, it keeps you absorbed in the story and interested in moving along.  As you play, you find yourself returning to the same places you've already been, because things change depending on season. For example, a rushing waterfall is impassable--until it's frozen over and you break its ice. A passageway is blocked with water, until you cause the water to drain away. And so on.  There is a glitch I've found on level 34. It erroneously says, "A majestic waterfall cascades over a narrow walkway, blocking your way forward." That message actually belongs on level 29.  There are quite a few puzzles along the way that have to be solved. If you're not great at solving puzzles, you might get frustrated.  I highly recommend this game, especially for people who enjoy puzzles and strategy/thinking games. If you're looking for an action/adventure/shoot-'em-up kind of game, this isn't it!

I am a big fan of Myst, and I've played dozens of point-and-click adventure games. The Lost City is a good 2-3 hour exploration experience, with immersive sound effects and beautiful scenery. I played with the music off because it started bothering me pretty quickly, but the little effects scattered throughout the game really drew me in to the world.  There were various levels of puzzles in the game; some were excellent, Myst-quality visual riddles, and others were generic sliding puzzles that felt like they were only there to extend the time it took to play. I liked how certain items had to actually be "used' in the world to be fully effective; not every action would immediately open the path but were intuitive enough that they never posed a problem.  The game generally had good affordances and priming; typically if I saw a puzzley situation, soon afterwards I would get the item that I knew would work perfectly. Other times I would discover an item and there would be nothing for me to do with it until halfway through the game.  Overall I had a good experience, and I will be watching Fire Maple Games for more of these types and quality of games.

I'd suggest being able to use the map to quick-travel between areas, too, since there isn't really any feeling of movement or connection between the individual screens that would be spoiled by doing this.
